Chutes has always been about more than just what it does right now. The most basic idea is chutes can take a resource, confidently say that it is indeed that resource and available for use, complete _any_ task with that resource, and validate that the task was actually completed. A lot of what chutes does currently is use GPU resources, and perform inference with those resources. This inference is globally distributed, fully validated, and it works really really well, there's no true equal in the cryptosphere. (inference stats: https://chutes.ai/app/research & https://openrouter.ai/provider/chutes)

But it really doesn't have to be just gpu resources or model inference, and from what Jon has said, he doesn't want it to be that limited. Chutes has already proven it can do GPU resources for inference tasks, very well, and now it's supporting what are called _jobs_, which allow you to run _any_ task, really any (in theory). Subnet validation, model training, heck, perhaps not in current form, but you could run an entire subnet using Chutes job system, complete with a validation and scoring mechanism. These also offer possibilities of things off the top of my head like outright server rentals, jupyter notebooks, comfy workflows, etc.

The current main product is tldr offering an easily deployable, easily scalable way to use AI models on a distributed network. It's currently being used by some businesses (text inference mainly), and by the next top two subnets to power various parts of their subnet (affine using the deployment system to deploy their miners models and inference to use them, and ridges using inference that it's agents ask for). Other subnets have used/use it for embeddings and stuff like that too. Miners on other subnets use it for various inference and embeddings as well.

With the massive compute backbone, Chutes can also expand its revenue with consumer apps like it says in the roadmap. The first two are Squad.ai and chat.chutes.ai. Squad is an agent builder with a lot of plans of its own, but the gist for the most basic end user is a "builder" type interface where they can connect different agentic tasks together to create a single agent. It also offers an SDK which allows you to be much more advanced, different target user there. Chutes chat is an actual app, not just a playground or demo page, and it has most of the features any other AI chat has, and some cool ones like message forking and such. This is another "normie" end user app designed for ease of use.

In the chat roleplay world for instance (multi billion dollar market, see googles 2.7 billion deal with character.ai, and groks companions), Chutes is literally the top provider for custom inference. People are hooking up their frontend apps (like janitorai) to chutes. People love using it so much that they went _rabid_ after chutes made a price/subscription change, it just goes to show how much they like using it that they're that unhinged 🤣.

It doesn't list any more apps/products on the roadmap, but there are a few more that are actively being worked on that I know of, and I don't think they're that far out either. Even the core product has changes in the roadmap for itself like TEE (so that businesses may run confidential workloads), a LLM pretraining service, an IPFS model distribution system, etc. (roadmap: https://chutes.ai/roadmap)

Chutes has already captured part of the non-crypto market, breaking through that "wall" that tends to exist when the word "crypto" is mentioned, it did it by starting in the crypto world too, not like they moved an outside userbase to it forcefully, but there's always more work to be done there. It's fast, it has new models basically the same hour they're released (and recently even before they're publicly released), and it works. The number of subscribers is steadily going up daily, but this is really just one revenue stream, one target audience, out of many. (sub/revenue: https://chutes.ai/app/research/payments)

Jon tends to move quick, and Chutes/rest of the team is already building several other products directly part of Chutes driving their own income streams as part of its overall revenue. People are quick to say it's just compute, just inference, but no, it's the product. That's why it hasn't been replicated. It's the product, not the resource that's different. They're right that anyone can offer compute, but not anyone can offer it in a manner that works as well as this, with an ecosystem built on top of it that has multiple revenue-driving products, all built with the same quality as the core platform.

So the idea that somehow Chutes will be limited to "just compute" is nonsense, it's the products built or being built on the top, and the external products and companies that run, and rely on it. Many will offer additional ways to drive revenue and growth to chutes as a whole, and it will be a good test of what chutes is capable of. Wait until Jon's bored too and has finished polishing, and Chutes will be producing intelligence in some sort of subnet within a subnet type of deal as well I bet, people forget he used to be big into training 😆.

🪂  We have support for "secrets" now, e.g. a private huggingface repo tokens and things of  that sort.

CLI usage example:
```bash
chutes secrets create \
  --purpose {chute ID or name} \
  --key HUGGING_FACE_HUB_TOKEN \
  --value hf_t...
```
These become environment variables added to the pod automagically, and in this case for example with `HUGGING_FACE_HUB_TOKEN` it means the model can be downloaded. Secrets are only passed along to pod after they've passed validation/gpu/code/etc. check, and it's passed back over an encrypted channel (from the https request to the validator with validation params).

Full example, deploying a private model:
```python
import os
from chutes.chute import NodeSelector
from chutes.chute.template.sglang import build_sglang_chute

chute = build_sglang_chute(
    username="chutes",
    readme="chutesai/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-private",
    model_name="chutesai/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-private",
    image="chutes/sglang:nightly-2025100200",
    concurrency=24,
    revision="d3e2d6da81921a870b55e987aabd3d5ea81f74cd",
    node_selector=NodeSelector(
        gpu_count=1,
        min_vram_gb_per_gpu=24,
        exclude=[
            "mi300x",
            "b200",
            "h200",
            "h100",
            "h100_sxm",
        ],
    ),
    engine_args=(
        "--cuda-graph-max-bs 24 "
        "--context-length 16384"
    ),
)
```
*notice there is NO reference to the HF token here, not necessary!*
Deploy the private chute:
```bash
chutes deploy private_example:chute
```
Create the secret (immediately):
```
chutes secrets create \
  --purpose chutesai/Llama-3.2-3B-Instruct-private \
  --key HUGGING_FACE_HUB_TOKEN \
  --value hf_t...
```

ALSO, in other news... The `--logging-enabled` flag has been removed entirely.  Logging is automatically enabled now for any private/user-deployed chute, and disabled for any public chute.

To use these features, upgrade: `pip install chutes==0.3.37`
Also, ICYMI, we removed the developer deposit requirement entirely. You do however, need a $50 min balance to be able to build custom images.

Rolled out some more updates: https://github.com/chutesai/chutes-miner/pull/55

Here's what's in it:

## General Updates
- **NVIDIA Install Fixes**: Updated packages to resolve NVIDIA driver installation issues.  The old packages could lead to minor version mismatches and cause fabricmanager to fail.  Added check for GCC/Kernel mismatch that could cause DKMS install to fail.  Added general sanity checks to make sure drivers match post install.
- **Cache Cleanup Fix**: Resolved issues with the cache cleanup job.  The job needed to be updated to work with the new cache structure.

## K3s Specific Updates
- **Network & Resource Syncing**: Improved handling of network issues and resource syncing between clusters. Clusters not actively syncing resources are now excluded from scheduling to avoid spamming the cluster.
- **Chart Annotations Fix**: Updated chart annotations to prevent mass pod evictions if node becomes un-schedulable.
- **Node IP Resolution**: Updated logic to resolve the monitor public IP using the `chutes/external-ip` label.  This solved issues where the host IP from the downward API was behind NAT without requiring manual configuration.
  - **Note**: If you deployed using previous playbooks, verify the `chutes/external-ip` label is set on the control node.
- **Kubeconfig Syncing Update**: The playbook to sync kubeconfig should handle changes to underlying clusters for the same inventory hostname. However, it doesn't clean up dangling nodes if a server is deleted. 
  - **Workaround**: Manually remove the kubeconfig from the Ansible user's home directory and re-run the playbook. This is a temporary solution until kubeconfig management is fully integrated into the `chutes-miner-cli` tool, phasing out Ansible-based management.

- To update:
  1. Verify the `chutes/external-ip` label is present on the control node, add if needed
  2. Run the `deploy-charts` playbook
  3. Run the `restart-k8s` playbook

**Support Note**: If you're facing issues setting up, please reach out, and I'll help resolve them. The only exception is GPU setup and NVIDIA driver issues.  Feel free to report them and I'll assist with common problems as best I can, but some provider-specific edge cases may require custom tweaks that can't be fully supported in the playbooks.
